<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="357" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1052,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kanmiya, 1971" authorityName="Kanmiya" authorityYear="1971" box="[776,1092,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ischaemi">
<emphasis box="[776,910,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">D. ischaemi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kanmiya, K." box="[917,1092,1052,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" pagination="157 - 180" refId="ref12133" refString="Kanmiya, K. (1971) Study on the genus Dicraeus Loew from Japan and Formosa (Diptera, Chloropidae). Mushi, 45, 157 - 180." type="journal article" year="1971">Kanmiya, 1971</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated from the latter by the following features: first flagellomere round dorsodistally; surstylus broad basally, with 3 spinous setae, suddenly narrowed at middle and curved; mesolobus (fused cerci) long, 2 times as long as surstylus, bent to venter of epandrium. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kanmiya" authorityYear="1971" box="[360,499,1160,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ischaemi">
<emphasis box="[360,499,1160,1184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">D. ischaemi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the first flagellomere has a dorsodistal angle; the surstylus is slender, slightly concave at middle, broadly round apically, and has 5 long thick setae; the cercus is slender, finger-like (
<bibRefCitation author="Kanmiya, K." pageId="6" pageNumber="357" pagination="157 - 180" refId="ref12133" refString="Kanmiya, K. (1971) Study on the genus Dicraeus Loew from Japan and Formosa (Diptera, Chloropidae). Mushi, 45, 157 - 180." type="journal article" year="1971">Kanmiya 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1366,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1293]" box="[199,1366,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1268,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Yang &amp; Nartshuk" authorityYear="2019" box="[747,822,1269,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Dicraeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus">
<emphasis box="[747,822,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="357">curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(“curved”), referring to the shape of mesolobus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
